								<p>
                                    <br>
                                    For the children living in Chinatown, St. Therese is more than just a Catholic Church. St. Therese is viewed as a safe, unifying environment that brings together children and the community as a whole.
                                    <br> <br />
                                    According to Tiffany Tse, Age 13:
                                    <br>
                                    “I go to school at St. Therese Chinese Catholic school. I have been there since pre-school. The community there in the school is safe, friendly, and it makes everyone feel accepted for being who they are. I feel like that type of environment reflects on the whole neighborhood of Chinatown.”
                                    <br> <br />
                                    Most children who attend St. Therese has been there for a long time, and St. Therese has helped them in many ways growing up. St. Therese helps bring the community of Chinatown together by participating in large events, such as the annual Lunar New Year Chinatown parade. Students attending St. Therese help with preparing the parade, as well as participating in major events.
                                    <br> <br />
                                    According to Connie Tan, Age 11:
                                    <br>
                                    “Even though I moved, I still visit Chinatown often and spend most of my time there. I would attend some of the parades, marathons, and annual summer fairs. My school, St. Therese School, is a big contributor to the parades. St. Therese students participate in these events, and that amazes me. I am very grateful that my parents decided to move here many years ago or else my life wouldn’t be what it is right now.”
                                    <br> <br />
                                    Although you might think St. Therese is mostly Chinese students, there are students from a wide variety of backgrounds. Despite the cultural differences, students like Chloe Culen, a Mexican-American attending St. Therese, is still able to enjoy major events such as the Summer Fair in Chinatown. 
                                    <br> <br />
                                    Chloe Culen states:
                                    <br>
                                    “In Chinatown there is much to do such as seasonal events like the Summer Fair. Our church, St. Therese, does contribute to this. The Summer Fair is a street festival that goes throughout the whole town. On one street there is our church, like I said, we contribute to this. We do things such as make food, lemonade, set up game stands, play music, and much more! The students from St. Therese help out to run the stands and have fun in the process.”
                                    <br> <br />
                                    Local events like these help keep the Chinatown community history alive. Both these and the great education it provides show how St. Therese serves both Chinatown and its surrounding communities.

								</p>
